Languages as optional are now considered as important in independent school curricula and elsewhere as basic subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics).
According to a survey carried out by the UK Employment and Skills Commission in 2014, 17 percent of all the reasons for employers’ difficulties in filling jobs were language skills.
As a result, language skills are becoming more and more compulsory to equip young people for their future careers.
As employability will depend heavily on languages in the future, these skills become essential in a globalised world.
No matter what career a person chooses in a second language, he or she will be far superior to others in the future if he or she has these skills that he or she needs throughout his or her life.
Being able to communicate directly with people from abroad will make people with several languages much more competitive.
According to a 2013 survey conducted by YouGov, involving more than 4 000 adults in the UK, 75 percent were unable to speak a foreign language sufficiently well to attend the interview, while French was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage of people, i.e. 15 percent.
That is why investing in language teaching is important for the children of the present.
Learning a number of languages, especially in developing countries, will improve the chances for children to find a meaningful job.
In Scotland, each school varies according to the languages it teaches.
Many schools focus on more classical modern languages, while others teach languages that are considered the most important for the United Kingdom in view of the future of 2020, such as Mandarins or Japanese.
Whatever the best interests of your child, there will always be many languages from which you can choose in an independent school with teaching staff and specialists in this field.
Scottish independent schools are ready to create a teaching environment that will equip children and provide them with the skills they need to live in the future.
There is no denying that languages remain vital for the future of the country in today's global business environment, and this must also be reflected in the education system.
Indeed, modern languages should certainly be regarded as "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this option, diversity and results for Scottish youth.
This must be done.
