National Trust listening to secret bat life
A new study carried out in one of the Scottish highlands estates aims to reveal how bats use the landscape to hunt for food.
Findings are expected to provide new knowledge of the behaviour of unique flying mammals and provide some guidance for future environmental activities.
Scientists of National Trust for Scotland will watch in their research the bats, soprano bats, brown ears and water mice in the gardens of Wester Roso Inverevo.
Special recorders will be placed in certain areas of the territory to allow monitoring of bat activity throughout the season.
The staff of the National Health Service and volunteers will also carry out mobile tests with handheld detectors.
Expert analysis of all sound recordings will determine the frequency of signals emitted by bats and the type of activity.
A map and report of residential habitats will then be created to help shape a detailed picture of behaviour across the landscape.
“National Trust for Scotland” (NTS) environmental adviser Rob Dewar hopes that the results will reveal which habitat is most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to identify the benefits of residential habitat maintenance, such as the creation of grasslands, as well as how best to maintain wooded areas in order to be suitable for bats and other associated species.
Over the past century, bat populations in Scotland and the United Kingdom have fallen.
They are threatened by construction and real estate development works that affect hatcheries and destroy residential habitats.
Wind power and lightning are also a threat, as are the flycatchers, some chemicals used to process construction materials, as well as hunting domestic cats.
Bats are not really blind.
However, ears rather than eyes help to catch the prey during night hunting.
Bats accurately determine the location of insects or obstacles in the flight path by means of a sophisticated echolocation.
The NTS, which is responsible for more than 270 historical buildings, 38 important gardens and 76 000 hectares of land throughout the country, is very responsible for bats.
There are ten trained experts who conduct regular investigations, hatchery inspections and sometimes rescue operations.
The organization has even created the first and only bat reserve in Scotland, in the Threave Manor in Damfris and Galloway, where eight of the ten bat species in Scotland live.
The manor overseer, David Thompson, says that the manor area is ideal for them.
“We have a great place for bats in Threave Manor,” he said.
- We have old buildings, lots of mature trees and great areas to live in.
But we do not know much about bats, so work here and in other places will help you to understand better what they need to flourish."
It stresses that it is particularly important to check for bats prior to the start of maintenance work, as the accidental destruction of one hatchery could lead to the death of up to 400 female and juveniles, which could lead to the destruction of the entire local population.
Bats shall be protected and shall not be killed, irritated or disturbed, nor shall the destruction of their hatcheries be prohibited.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish bat guard officer, called on the public to contribute to the rescue of bats.
She said: “We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and we don’t know how many local species are going. ”
